Text: The sparrows chirped from a nearby branch, annoyed and curious.
One hopped closer, bold and unafraid.
Jonas felt a tiny bubble in his chest—something like warmth but unfamiliar, fragile.
Weller brought him tea afterward, insisting he sit with her on her balcony.

She told him stories about the neighborhood: the building super who loved classical music, the teenager across the hall who practiced violin at inconvenient hours, the couple upstairs expecting their first child.
Jonas hadn’t known any of this.
After he left, the blue curtain in his apartment felt heavier than usual.
That evening he stood in front of it, fingers wrapped around the edge of the fabric.
The streetlights outside glowed faintly through the weave.
It was the glow of a world continuing, indifferent to his grief but not hostile to his return.
A delivery cyclist stopped at a red light.
Tree branches still bare from winter.
